{"findings":[{"id":"F-001","severity":"Critical","confidence":"high","title":"`deposit()` credits stake from the requested amount without verifying tokens were actually received","locations":["test/ExploitPOC.t.sol:11","test/ExploitPOC.t.sol:12","test/ExploitPOC.t.sol:13","test/ExploitPOC.t.sol:14"],"claim":"`MockStaking.deposit()` only checks `allowance()` and then blindly calls `transferFrom()` before crediting `balances[msg.sender][tokenAddress] += amount`. It neither checks the boolean return value nor compares the contract's token balance before and after the transfer, so it can over-credit deposits when `transferFrom()` returns `false` or when the token transfers less than `amount` (fee-on-transfer / deflationary behavior).","impact":"An attacker can mint unbacked stake for the full requested amount and later withdraw real tokens once honest liquidity for that same asset exists in the pool. In the false-return case this can be completely zero-cost, creating direct insolvency and theft of other users' funds; in the short-transfer case it leaves the pool undercollateralized and socializes the deficit onto later withdrawers.","paths":["Approve the staking contract for a token whose `transferFrom()` can fail softly or transfer less than requested.","Call `deposit(token, amount, ...)`; the staking contract records the full `amount` regardless of how many tokens it actually receives.","Wait for honest users to deposit real liquidity of that same token.","Call `withdraw(token, amount)` and drain the real liquidity against the inflated internal balance."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-003","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"`withdraw()` can burn user balances without paying tokens when `transfer()` fails softly","locations":["test/ExploitPOC.t.sol:17","test/ExploitPOC.t.sol:18","test/ExploitPOC.t.sol:19","test/ExploitPOC.t.sol:20"],"claim":"`MockStaking.withdraw()` decrements `balances[msg.sender][tokenAddress]` before calling `token.transfer(msg.sender, amount)` and never checks whether that transfer succeeded. If the token returns `false` instead of reverting, the transaction still succeeds after the user's recorded balance has already been reduced.","impact":"Once the pool is undercollateralized or the token otherwise fails soft on transfer, users can lose their withdrawal claim permanently while receiving no tokens. This turns an accounting shortfall into direct user fund loss and permanent lockup of remaining claims.","paths":["The pool becomes unable to satisfy the requested withdrawal amount for a false-returning token, for example after the phantom-deposit issue above.","A user calls `withdraw(token, amount)`.","The contract subtracts the user's internal balance first.","`token.transfer()` returns `false` rather than reverting, so the withdrawal transaction completes with no payout.","The user's claim is burned even though no tokens were received."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]}],"rejected_candidates":[{"title":"Reentrancy across `withdraw()` and `deposit()` lets a callback token drain the same pool repeatedly","source_agents":["codex"],"reason":"Not a standalone issue here. `withdraw()` already deducts balance before the external call, so there is no same-balance double-withdraw against honest tokens. The proposed loop still relies on the same malicious/soft-failing token behavior already captured by F-001, making it derivative rather than incremental protocol risk."},{"title":"Anyone can permissionlessly create staking markets for arbitrary attacker-controlled tokens","source_agents":["codex"],"reason":"Permissionless token/epoch initialization alone is not sufficient harm. Any loss path still depends on the unsafe token-transfer assumptions already covered by F-001/F-003, and no cross-pool or unavoidable harm beyond the attacker-chosen token market is shown."}]}
